        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Bromley. | Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan 27 1869</date>
                    <salute>My dear Phillips</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Your book on Vesuvius has not arrived, but has perhaps been sent to my London address, or may come by Railway. I must however send you my very sincere thanks for this present, &amp; even more so your very kind note<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6279.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Phillips 1869</ref> had just been published (<hi rend="italic">Publishers’ Circular</hi>, 1 February 1869, pp. 67, 73). CD’s copy is in the Darwin Library–Down. CD refers to the London address (6 Queen Anne Street) of his brother, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1211.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Erasmus Alvey Darwin</ref>. Phillips’s letter to CD has not been found.</note>
        </div>        
            
